




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Corporate Conservatism and Relative Compensation
AU  - Zwiebel, Jeffrey
Y1  - 1995/02/01
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261973
DO  - 10.1086/261973
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1
EP  - 25
VL  - 103
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper demonstrates that in a simple setting with managerial concern for reputation and asymmetric information on ability, most managers may refrain from undertaking innovations that stochastically dominate an industry standard. Common components of uncertainty lead to market inferences of managerial ability based on relative performance. Managers who undertake the industry standard are consequently evaluated with a more accurate benchmark than those innovating. Discontinuities in compensation when performance is low (because of firings) lead managers to have differing valuations of an accurate benchmark, depending on type. In particular, very high and very low ability managers are more likely to undertake superior innovations than those of average ability.
AB  - This paper demonstrates that in a simple setting with managerial concern for reputation and asymmetric information on ability, most managers may refrain from undertaking innovations that stochastically dominate an industry standard. Common components of uncertainty lead to market inferences of managerial ability based on relative performance. Managers who undertake the industry standard are consequently evaluated with a more accurate benchmark than those innovating. Discontinuities in compensation when performance is low (because of firings) lead managers to have differing valuations of an accurate benchmark, depending on type. In particular, very high and very low ability managers are more likely to undertake superior innovations than those of average ability.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261973
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261973
Y2  - 2024/03/22
