TY  - JOUR
T1  - Anarchy and its Breakdown
AU  - Hirshleifer, Jack
Y1  - 1995/02/01
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261974
DO  - 10.1086/261974
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 26
EP  - 52
VL  - 103
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Anarchy, defined as a system in which participants can seize and defend resources without regulation from above, is not chaos but rather a spontaneous order. However, anarchy is fragile and may dissolve either into formless "amorphy" or into a more organized system such as hierarchy. Under anarchy, each contestant balances between productive exploitation of the current resource base and fighting to acquire or defend resources. Anarchy is sustainable only when there are strongly diminishing returns to fighting effort (the "decisiveness parameter" is sufficiently low) and incomes exceed the viability minimum. These considerations explain many features of animal and human conflict.
AB  - Anarchy, defined as a system in which participants can seize and defend resources without regulation from above, is not chaos but rather a spontaneous order. However, anarchy is fragile and may dissolve either into formless "amorphy" or into a more organized system such as hierarchy. Under anarchy, each contestant balances between productive exploitation of the current resource base and fighting to acquire or defend resources. Anarchy is sustainable only when there are strongly diminishing returns to fighting effort (the "decisiveness parameter" is sufficiently low) and incomes exceed the viability minimum. These considerations explain many features of animal and human conflict.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261974
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261974
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Economics of Breakdowns, Checkups, and Cures
AU  - Taylor, Curtis R.
Y1  - 1995/02/01
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261975
DO  - 10.1086/261975
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 53
EP  - 74
VL  - 103
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - A market in which the owner of a durable good, X, contracts with an expert for diagnostic and treatment services is studied. Good X may be in one of three states: "health," "disease," or "failure." Only experts can determine whether X is healthy or diseased and perform treatment. The owner cannot tell whether recommended treatment is really needed. This creates an information-based demand for health insurance by risk-neutral consumers. Imperfections in the market for spot insurance may give rise to free diagnostic checks, strategic procrastination, and long-term health maintenance agreements.
AB  - A market in which the owner of a durable good, X, contracts with an expert for diagnostic and treatment services is studied. Good X may be in one of three states: "health," "disease," or "failure." Only experts can determine whether X is healthy or diseased and perform treatment. The owner cannot tell whether recommended treatment is really needed. This creates an information-based demand for health insurance by risk-neutral consumers. Imperfections in the market for spot insurance may give rise to free diagnostic checks, strategic procrastination, and long-term health maintenance agreements.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261975
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261975
Y2  - 2024/03/22
